<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-01T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-01T16:00:00-05:00" n="285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/543: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-01T16:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">April 1,
                                        1927—4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>113. Your 305, March 31, 6 p.m. Protests have also been filed here by
                            Standard Oil Company as well as by Texas Company. Department is
                            informing companies that in view of grave situation existing at Changsha
                            and Chungking Department authorized action recommended by your telegram
                            No. 254 of March 25, 9 [<hi rend="italic">4</hi>] p.m. Standard Oil
                            Company informs us that British and Japanese are not taking action
                            similar to this. Can you inform Department on this point?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>